Wisconsin non-convictions are not handled through 973.015 adult conviction expungement. They route through DOJ-CIB fingerprint/arrest removal.
A person may qualify for arrest fingerprint record removal if they were:
arrested and released without charge;
found not guilty;
had the charges dismissed by the court or prosecutor;
or no charges were filed by the prosecutor.
Wisconsin DOJ says the request uses DJ-LE-250B, requires fingerprints, has no fee, and if the removed Wisconsin arrest information had been forwarded to the FBI, the FBI will be contacted to remove it from the FBI record.
Wilma caution: All charges from that arrest event must be cleared. If one charge from the same arrest resulted in conviction, DOJ-CIB removal may be blocked.

Wisconsin has a special route for people convicted, adjudicated delinquent, or found not guilty by reason of mental disease or defect for prostitution under 944.30, if the offense was committed as a result of being a victim of trafficking for purposes of a commercial sex act.
The person may move the court to vacate the conviction/adjudication/finding or expunge the record if:
the person was a trafficking victim for commercial sex;
the 944.30 violation resulted from that trafficking;
the motion includes facts and may include court records, immigration-related certifications, official government documentation, or other credible evidence;
the motion was made with due diligence, considering safety concerns;
the district attorney is served or notified and has an opportunity to respond;
the court finds the person will benefit and society will not be harmed. ("https://law.justia.com/codes/wisconsin/chapter-973/section-973-015/")
Wilma trauma rule: Do not force details. Ask only:

Was this prostitution-related case connected to trafficking, coercion, exploitation, survival circumstances, or someone forcing or directing you?

Then route to manual/legal review.

Wilma should start with two records:
1 Wisconsin Circuit Court Access / court docket for the case details.
2 Wisconsin DOJ-CIB criminal history for fingerprint-supported arrest/conviction information.
Wisconsin DOJ says its Centralized Criminal History database contains demographic data, arrest/charge information, final dispositions, sentences, DNA registrations, and DOC admission/release notices; it is based on arrest fingerprint cards submitted by law enforcement. ("https://www.wisdoj.gov/Pages/CriminalJusticeServices/criminal-background-check.aspx")
Wilma should collect:
full name and prior names;
date of birth;
county and circuit court case number;
arrest date;
offense date;
exact charge and statute;
offense class;
maximum possible imprisonment;
age at offense;
sentencing date;
whether the judge ordered expungement at sentencing;
sentence type: probation, jail, prison, fine, restitution, community service, supervision;
sentence completion date;
whether probation was revoked;
whether any subsequent conviction occurred before sentence completion;
whether the case was dismissed, no-filed, or acquitted;
whether all charges from the arrest event were cleared;
whether the case involved traffic/DOT records, civil forfeiture, OWI, violent offense, stalking, child abuse, sex offense, school-staff sexual assault, concealing death of child, or trafficking/prostitution facts.
